name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Singleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Yorkshire):","habitational name from Singleton (Lancashire), probably from Old English <i>scingol</i> ‘shingle, wooden roof tile’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Bearers of this surname are said to be descended from Ughtred <i>de Sinleton</i>, holder of lands in Amounderness wapentake (Lancashire) <i>c.</i> 1160–90. This name was first recorded in Ireland in 1308 and firmly established in Louth and Monaghan during the 17th century.","habitational name from Singleton (Sussex), probably from Old English <i>sængel</i>, <i>sengel</i> ‘bundle, tuft’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Singelton","meanings":["English: variant of   Singleton  ."]},{"name":"Shingleton","meanings":["English: late medieval variant of   Singleton  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":23,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":54,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Singleton was born in 1236, in Kirkham, Lancashire, England, his father, William de Singleton, was 33 and his mother, Catherine de Meols, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Katherine. He died in 1292, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1236–1292":"1236–1292","1226–1292":"1226–1292","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1274–1326":"1274–1326","1204–1262":"1204–1262","1211–Female":"1211–Surnud","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1226":"1226","1236":"1236","1211":"1211","1255":"1255","1233":"1233","Aft 1262":"pärast 1262","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Broughton, Lancashire, England":"Broughton, Lancashire, England","Kirkham, Lancashire, England":"Kirkham, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1236–1292":"1236–1292","1226–1292":"1226–1292","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1233–Male":"1233–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1274–1326":"1274–1326","1204–1262":"1204–1262","1211–Female":"1211–Kuollut","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1204":"1204","1226":"1226","123